# Per-machine toolchain paths (TASS / PYTHON overrides)
documents/local.make

# Emulator memory dumps (x16emu writes dump*.bin, Box16 writes dump*.txt)
dump*.bin
dump*.txt
memory_stats.txt

# Python
__pycache__/
*.pyc

# Transient: pcode.py emits scripts/pcodeconstraw.py here, the Makefile then
# moves it to common-scripts/. The directory itself must exist to build.
source/common-source/scripts/

# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
# Build output.
#
# build/ holds a MIX of checked-in sources (hello.bas, balls.bas, PROTEUS7.PRG)
# and generated files, so it cannot be ignored wholesale -- only the products.
#
# code.lbl and code.lst are the worst offenders: 64tass emits their symbols in a
# nondeterministic order, so they churned on every single build even when nothing
# changed. (code.prg is byte-identical across rebuilds -- the codegen itself is
# deterministic; it is only these dumps that are not.)
# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
source/*/build/code.lbl
source/*/build/code.lst
source/*/build/code.prg
source/*/build/dump.bin
source/*/build/*.pcode
source/*/build/*.tokenised

# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
# Generated by the randomised compiler-runtime suites.
#
# Each run writes a fresh random program (REM *** SEED nnnn ***), so all of this
# changed on every test run. examples/*.bas is just a copy of the LAST run's
# program -- a record, not an input.
#
# NOT ignored here: source/runtime/testing/code/code.bin. It looks like a test
# intermediate (the suite overwrites it with CODE.BIN and replays it via
# "make -C source/runtime run"), but runtime/testing/testend.asm does
# .binary "code/code.bin" -- it is a REQUIRED BUILD INPUT, and untracking it
# breaks "make libs" on a fresh clone. A plain build never rewrites it; only the
# randomised suite does, and that is a deliberate act whose diff is worth seeing.
# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
source/unit-tests/compiler-runtime/build/
source/unit-tests/compiler-runtime/examples/*.bas
source/unit-tests/compiler-runtime/CODE.BIN

# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
# source/gpc front end. GPC.BASL (BASLOAD source) is tokenised into testing/GPC.PRG by
# build_basl.py driving the emulator -- both GPC.BASL and GPC.PRG SHIP and are tracked in
# testing/. Ignore only the tokenise scratch (a one-line driver, an echo log) and the
# #SYMFILE debug map. The retired Prog8 front end sits in source/gpc/old-archive/: its .P8
# source and bump script are kept (tracked), but not its binary or build scratch.
# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
testing/GPCBLD.BAS
testing/GPCBLD.LOG
testing/GPC.SYM
source/gpc/old-archive/GPC.PRG
source/gpc/old-archive/build/

# The release used to be bundled into testing/blitz.zip (mkzip.py). That was dropped:
# nothing consumed it, and it was a git-tracked binary rebuilt on every release.
testing/blitz.zip

# release.zip is the packaged download, built by release.sh / release.bat. Like the
# old blitz.zip it is a rebuilt-on-demand artifact, not something to commit.
release.zip

# GPC.INPUT is generated next to the compiler by "make -C source/application";
# the one that ships is testing/GPC.INPUT.
source/application/GPC.INPUT

# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
# testing/ is now the shipping release directory (moved here from release/) AND
# the scratch area for batch-testing user BASIC programs. The release artifacts
# in testing/ ARE tracked; only the two scratch subdirs below are ignored:
# testing/prg-batch/ is the queue (drop source PRGs in), testing/archive/ holds
# the ones already run. Both are transient personal test material -- inputs we
# compile to find compiler gaps, not part of the project or the build.
# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
testing/prg-batch/
testing/archive/
gpc-release.zip
gpc-release-*.zip
